03418nam a22006375i 9780292753563DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211998txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927535637 a10.7560/7773162doi  a(DE-B1597)586663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPQ7298.29.O44bA8613 1998 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a8632211 aSolares, Ignacio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLost in the City: Tree of Desire and Serafin :bTwo novels by Ignacio Solares /cIgnacio Solares. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1998  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tTree of Desire -- tSerafín0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCristina, the young protagonist of Tree of Desire, and her little brother Joaquín run away from a home that is outwardly normal, but inwardly disfunctional. Lost on the streets of Mexico City, they confront some of the most terrifying aspects of city life. Or is it all a dream? The story suggests, without confirming, that sexual abuse has driven Cristina to her desperate escape. But is it an escape? Are they awakening from a dream, or reentering a nightmare? Serafín, too, is lost in the city. Searching for his father who has deserted the family, he is virtually helpless amid the city dangers. Serafín finds compassion in surprising places, but will he survive to return to his mother and their rural village? These two novels by one of Mexico's premier writers illuminate many aspects of contemporary Mexican life. Solares describes Mexico's different social classes with Dickensian realism. His focus on young protagonists, unusual in Mexican literature, opens a window onto problems of children's vulnerability that know no national borders. At the same time, his use of elements of the fantastic and the paranormal, and his evocative writing style, make reading his novels a most pleasurable experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSolares, Ignacio,-1945--Translations into English. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBrushwood, Carolyn.1 aBrushwood, John.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77731640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292753563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292753563/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK